Network Verification Background Knowledge

Understanding eBGP, Route Propagation, and Route Policies

eBGP Basics

External Border Gateway Protocol (eBGP) is the standard routing protocol used to exchange routes between different autonomous systems (ASes) on the Internet. Each AS is managed by an independent administrative entity (e.g., an ISP, a large enterprise network), and eBGP ensures that routing information can flow between them. Routers enabling eBGP often apply policies to control which routes to accept, advertise, or prefer.

Route Propagation

Routing information in BGP is propagated from the destination network toward the source. However, when forwarding data packets, the direction is reversed: packets travel from the source host toward the destination, following the best path entries learned through propagation.

As shown in the figure above, the green lines represent the route propagation paths determined by configured route policies and best-route selection, while the blue lines represent the actual data packet forwarding paths. ISP1 propagates the route 192.0.2.0/24 to router R1. If R1 selects this route as the best path, it then advertises the route to router R3. Subsequently, R3 propagates the route to the customer network. Based on these advertisements, data packets are forwarded along the corresponding paths.

Therefore, by controlling route propagation policies and best-path selection, we can effectively control the forwarding paths and behaviors of data packets in the network.

Route Selection

Routers may receive multiple candidate routes to the same destination. To avoid loops and inconsistencies, BGP defines a best route selection process, which is applied in a top-down order: the router selects the first route that satisfies the highest-priority criterion that differentiates the candidates.

The typical criteria for BGP route selection are:

  • Highest local preference (operator-defined priority).
  • Shortest AS-path (fewer autonomous systems traversed).
  • Lowest MED (Multi-Exit Discriminator).
  • Lowest router ID (operator-configured BGP router-id).

If multiple routing protocols advertise the same prefix, the router chooses the route with the lowest administrative distance. For example, an static route (AD=1) is preferred over an eBGP-learned route (AD=20).

Only the single overall best path——or equal-cost multiple paths (ECMP)——is installed in the routing table and propagated to the eBGP neighbor.

In this user study, the BGP route selection process only involves AS-path length. Other BGP attributes (such as local preference or MED) are not part of the testing configurations and are therefore ignored. In our testing configurations, equal-cost routes are determined solely by AS-path length: routes with the same AS-path length are treated as equivalent, while a route with a shorter AS-path is preferred as the single best route. (Note: In this study, multi-path relax is assumed to be enabled by default, allowing paths with different AS-paths but equal AS-path length to be installed as ECMP routes.)

As shown in the figure above, ISP2 propagates the route 198.51.100.0/24 to router R2. R2 then selects this route as the best path and advertises it to routers R1 and R3. Subsequently, R1 selects this route as the best path and advertises it to router R3. (Note: For illustration, router names (e.g., R1, R2, ISP1) are used to represent corresponding AS numbers in the AS-paths.)

Router R3 now receives two following candidate routes to the same destination. Following the BGP best-path selection process, R3 selects the route from R2 as the best path, installs it in the routing table, and propagates it to its eBGP neighbors.

  • The route from R2 has AS-path (ISP2, R2) with an AS-path length of 2.
  • The route from R1 has AS-path (ISP2, R2, R1) with an AS-path length of 3.

As shown in the figure above, ISP2 propagates the route 198.51.100.0/24 to router R2. R2 selects this route as the best path, prepends its own AS number (R2) to the AS-path attribute, and advertises the updated route to R3; in parallel, R2 propagates the route to R1 according to default export policy. Subsequently, R1 selects this route as the best path and advertises it to R3. (Note: For illustration, router names (e.g., R1, R2, ISP1) are used to represent corresponding AS numbers in the AS-paths.)

Router R3 now receives two candidate routes to the same destination with equal AS-path length. Following the BGP best-path selection process, R3 installs both routes as ECMP routes and propagates them to its eBGP neighbors:

  • The route from R2 has AS-path (ISP2, R2, R2) with an AS-path length of 3.
  • The route from R1 has AS-path (ISP2, R2, R1) with an AS-path length of 3.

Route Policy route-map

The route-map is a central policy mechanism in BGP configuration. It works like a sequence of conditional rules, where each rule may:

  • Match specific conditions, such as prefixs, communities, and other route attributes.
  • Take actions on routes: modify attributes and accept the route, directly accept the route, or filter it.

Network operators use route-maps to:

  • Block or allow certain prefixes (thereby controlling which routes are propagated).
  • Adjust AS-path (thereby controlling the AS-path length) or other route attributes.
  • Attach or remove community tags (thereby influencing downstream route policy decisions).

Route-map Naming Conventions

Firstly, we introduce the inbound and outbound route-map policies along with their naming conventions. As shown in the figure above, green squares represent inbound route-map policies, and blue squares represent outbound route-map policies. All route-map names on router R1 are as follows; other route-maps use similar naming conventions:

  • R1_IN_FROM_ISP1: Inbound BGP route-map on R1 for routes learned from ISP1.
  • R1_OUT_TO_ISP1: Outbound BGP route-map on R1 applied to updates sent to ISP1.
  • R1_OUT_TO_R3: Outbound BGP route-map on R1 applied to updates sent to R3.

Simple Example: R1_IN_FROM_ISP1

R1_IN_FROM_ISP1 is an inbound BGP route-map on R1 applied to routes learned from ISP1. It controls which routes are accepted and how their attributes are modified before being installed in R1's routing table.

!!! Inbound BGP route policy on R1 for routes learned from ISP1. !!!
route-map R1_IN_FROM_ISP1 permit 10
match ip address prefix-list isp1_network
set community 400:100 additive
!
route-map R1_IN_FROM_ISP1 deny 100
match ip address prefix-list default_ips
!
!
!!! Prefix-list definitions on R1. !!!
ip prefix-list default_ips seq 5 permit 0.0.0.0/0 le 32
!
ip prefix-list isp1_network seq 5 permit 192.0.2.0/24 ge 24
ip prefix-list isp1_network seq 10 permit 198.51.100.0/24 ge 24

The explanation of route-map R1_IN_FROM_ISP1:

  • The first rule (permit 10) matches routes in the isp1_network prefix-list, which includes 192.0.2.0/24 and 198.51.100.0/24, sets community 400:100 (additive), and accepts the route. This marks these ISP1 routes for downstream policy decisions.
  • The second rule (deny 100) matches routes in the default_ips prefix-list (0.0.0.0/0) and denies them.
  • Rules are applied in order: the first matching rule is executed, and subsequent rules are ignored for that route.

Complex Example: Multiple Route-Maps on R2

R2_IN_FROM_ISP2 is an inbound BGP route-map on R2 applied to routes learned from ISP2.

R2_OUT_TO_ISP2 is an outbound route-map applied to updates sent to ISP2.

R2_OUT_TO_R3 is an outbound route-map applied to updates sent to R3.

!!! Inbound BGP route policy on R2 for routes learned from ISP2. !!!
route-map R2_IN_FROM_ISP2 permit 10
match ip address prefix-list isp2_network
set community 500:200 additive
!
route-map R2_IN_FROM_ISP2 deny 100
match ip address prefix-list default_ips
!
!
!!! Outbound BGP route policy on R2 applied to updates sent to ISP2. !!!
route-map R2_OUT_TO_ISP2 deny 10
match community 400100
!
route-map R2_OUT_TO_ISP2 permit 100
match ip address prefix-list default_ips
!
!
!!! Outbound BGP route policy on R2 applied to updates sent to R3. !!!
route-map R2_OUT_TO_R3 permit 10
set as-path prepend 200
!
!
!!! Prefix-list definitions on R2. !!!
ip prefix-list default_ips seq 5 permit 0.0.0.0/0 le 32
!
ip prefix-list isp2_network seq 5 permit 198.51.100.0/24 ge 24
!
!
!!! Community-list definitions on R2. !!!
ip community-list 400100 permit 400:100

The explanation of route-map R2_IN_FROM_ISP2:

  • The first rule (permit 10) matches routes in the isp2_network prefix-list, which includes 198.51.100.0/24. It sets a community tag 500:200 (additive) and accepts the route. This marks the ISP2 routes for downstream policy decisions.
  • The second rule (deny 100) matches routes in the default_ips prefix-list (0.0.0.0/0) and denies them, preventing these routes from being accepted.
  • Rules are applied in order: the first matching rule is executed, and subsequent rules are ignored for that route.

The explanation of route-map R2_OUT_TO_ISP2:

  • The first rule (deny 10) matches routes in the community-list 400100 (i.e., tagged with community 400:100) and denies them, preventing these routes from being advertised to ISP2.
  • The second rule (permit 100) matches all other routes in the default_ips prefix-list and allows them to be advertised.
  • Rules are applied in order, with the first matching rule taking effect.

The explanation of route-map R2_OUT_TO_R3:

  • The single rule (permit 10) prepends AS-number 200 to the AS-path of all outbound routes before advertising them to R3.
  • This increases the AS-path length, affecting best-path selection in downstream routers.
